WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.110 --> 00:00:34.930
&gt;&gt;Female Introducer: Hi everyone. Welcome.
On behalf of the Authors@Google program, I

00:00:34.930 --> 00:00:38.680
am excited to welcome back Mary Roach. As
one of you put is, Mary is one of the funniest

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:40.860
and most madcap of science writers. She is
of the firm belief that there is no question

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:42.220
to goofy to ask, or boring to Google. Her
previous books include: "Stiff: The Curious

00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:43.410
Lives of Human Cadavers," "Spook: Science
Tackles the Afterlife" and "Bonk: The Curious

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:44.770
Coupling of Science and Sex." Her newest book
is "Packing for Mars: The Curious Science

00:00:44.770 --> 00:00:45.770
of Life in the Void."

00:00:45.770 --> 00:00:50.950
Now Mary probably had aspirations of becoming
an astronaut, but Mary has done us the courtesy

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:58.220
of researching all things that our eight-year-old
selves forgot to think of like, how you keep

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:05.059
clean up in space? Showers don't work without
gravity. What do you eat? Mom's Rice Krispy

00:01:05.059 --> 00:01:07.300
treats probably won't meet NASA's nutrition
standards. And most importantly, where do

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:13.370
you go to the bathroom? Toilets don't work
in zero G either. Lucky for us the book goes

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:14.890
into extreme detail.

00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:15.890
[Laughter]

00:01:15.890 --> 00:01:22.520
About these questions and more, here to tell
us more, please welcome Mary Roach.

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:23.520
[Applause]

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:31.060
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: Thank you. This is my Tang substitute.
[laughter] On my book tour I actually, my

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:39.170
publicist thought it would be a great idea
to have Tang in the bookstores for everybody

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:41.270
so I would dutifully drink Tang until I realized
my kidneys were starting probably to fluoresce.

00:01:41.270 --> 00:01:42.270
[Laughter]

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:44.689
Tang. I always start by telling people, Tang
is not a NASA invention. Actually I'm gonna

00:01:44.689 --> 00:01:52.660
use this guy. Ooh, it's got a cord. This is
very old school--I like this. Can everybody

00:01:52.660 --> 00:02:02.810
hear OK? Is this even turned on? Is it turned
on, right? OK. I feel like Merv Griffin.

00:02:02.810 --> 00:02:03.810
[Laughter]

00:02:03.810 --> 00:02:13.310
No, anyway. But Tang, Tang is not an invention
of NASA. NASA just would order it from the

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:18.709
store, like anybody else. Is it called a commercial
off-the-shelf product, COTS product, and NASA

00:02:18.709 --> 00:02:23.920
actually does a lot of purchasing of COTS,
commercial off-the-shelf products, including

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:28.180
the diapers that they wear in the big, puffy
space walking suits when they go to repair

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:32.100
to the solar panel or whatever, they are wearing
an adult diaper. And I don't know what they

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:36.190
are using now, but for a period of time, this
is true, the public affairs office told me

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:38.260
this--it was a brand called Rejoice.

00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:39.629
[Laughter]

00:02:39.629 --> 00:02:46.420
Just like the most optimistic name for an
adult diaper that you can imagine. Anyway,

00:02:46.420 --> 00:02:54.280
so, my book is a book about space and astronauts,
but not really a typical book about space

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.720
and astronauts. I don't know if there necessarily
a typical, but there's a lot of sort of heroics

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:02.900
and bravely going and coming back. And you
have Jim Lovell and Apollo 13 fighting, his

00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:08.640
crew and him fighting for their lives and
the way of the moon, explosion, all of that.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:15.180
It's not that kind of book. I did talk to
Captain Lovell, but not about Apollo 13, I

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:21.069
talked to him about Gemini 7. Gemini 7 was
fascinating to me because it was the longest

00:03:21.069 --> 00:03:26.660
mission to date. It was a two-week mission.
It was the first time people had been in space

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:30.489
for that long. Before that it had been a few
days and part of what they were trying to

00:03:30.489 --> 00:03:36.010
figure out, at that point, was, is two weeks
in a spacesuit, in a cramped space, without

00:03:36.010 --> 00:03:41.319
a bathroom, without a shower, it is just too
horrible for a human being? It is too much

00:03:41.319 --> 00:03:47.100
to stand? It is too awful? Do you get too
disgusting? So, that's actually what they

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:54.580
were looking into, and I did, you know, you
can look through the transcript, the mission

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:59.769
transcript, for all of the missions that NASA's
done. There are those big huge PDF files that

00:03:59.769 --> 00:04:06.330
you can read, and there's a moment at Gemini,
Gemini 7, where the flight surgeon comes on

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:10.200
the radio, because there is a lot of information
back and forth, it's a medical mission essentially.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:13.830
And the flight surgeon comes on the line and
he is talking to Commander Borman, who is

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:20.629
the other, there are two of them in the capsule.
He is like, exact words were, "Gemini 7, this

00:04:20.629 --> 00:04:27.309
is the flight surgeon. Have you had any dandruff
problems up there, Frank?" I mean, this to

00:04:27.309 --> 00:04:33.129
me is, the word "dandruff" in a mission transcript,
in an official NASA mission transcript, I

00:04:33.129 --> 00:04:37.469
don't know why this just delighted me. And
further on the word "lotion." There are like

00:04:37.469 --> 00:04:43.119
two grown men, orbiting earth, discussing
skin care. Commander Borman, Frank Borman,

00:04:43.119 --> 00:04:48.930
was sort of difficult guy, and after a while
he stopped answering all questions about personal

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:54.420
products and skin care. It was like compromising
the overall manliness of the mission.

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:55.490
[Laughter]

00:04:55.490 --> 00:05:02.469
But you kind of, you did have to feel bad
for them because this is zero gravity and

00:05:02.469 --> 00:05:06.349
if you do have dandruff, it's not going to
fall to your shoulders, it's not going to

00:05:06.349 --> 00:05:11.710
fall to the floor. It kind of hovers and I
actually asked Jim Lovell. I got Jim Lovell

00:05:11.710 --> 00:05:16.699
to call me back, I think because everyone
wants to talk about Apollo 13 and nobody never

00:05:16.699 --> 00:05:21.779
asks him about Gemini 7. So, you know, we
got on the phone and I said, "So was it just

00:05:21.779 --> 00:05:25.129
likes a snow globe in there?"

00:05:25.129 --> 00:05:26.129
[Laughter]

00:05:26.129 --> 00:05:35.789
He said, "Mary you are investigating a rather
and usual aspect, a space flight."

00:05:35.789 --> 00:05:36.789
[Laughter]

00:05:36.789 --> 00:05:42.960
Anyway, so, I wanted, you know, the book is
about astronauts, it's about life in space,

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:49.419
but it's also about space on earth because
I found out that, because space is this really,

00:05:49.419 --> 00:05:55.249
extreme, hostile, unusual, expensive place
where nothing that works down here works the

00:05:55.249 --> 00:05:59.410
same as it does up there. And you need to
test it, and you need to kind of test it in

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:03.949
zero gravity if possible, and that is a little
tricky to do. You have to essentially put

00:06:03.949 --> 00:06:10.969
it on one of these planes that kind of flies
like this. So anyway, but they do, they test

00:06:10.969 --> 00:06:18.969
everything. They test even the toilets. OK,
now toilets, some people take gravity a little

00:06:18.969 --> 00:06:25.039
bit for granted, I think. You kind of think
about water system. You know, there's the

00:06:25.039 --> 00:06:29.249
sewage and the water and you don't realize
gravity plays a big role here because what

00:06:29.249 --> 00:06:37.289
you have is, you have a growing mass, OK,
that's being extruded and with more mass you

00:06:37.289 --> 00:06:42.610
have greater gravitation, and at a certain
point the material breaks free and falls down

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:47.300
into the toilet where it's whisked away and
everybody is happy. Well, in zero gravity

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:59.199
this doesn't happen, it just kind of hovers.
And, so, the zero gravity toilet has to give

00:06:59.199 --> 00:07:03.949
you what they call, NASA Waste Management
people call "Good Separation." This is the

00:07:03.949 --> 00:07:09.990
Holy Grail of the waste management engineer
at NASA. Good separation. So the toilet now

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:14.649
has to provide that separation and the way
it does it is by air flow. It sort of entrains

00:07:14.649 --> 00:07:21.319
the bolas. I've got a lot of euphemisms out
of that. My time with the NASA Waste Management

00:07:21.319 --> 00:07:24.539
Department. So you didn't train the bolas?
Well you have airflow doing that. It's basically

00:07:24.539 --> 00:07:31.029
like sitting on a Shop-Vac. I was gonna say
shitting on a Sop Vac. [Laughter] Like sitting

00:07:31.029 --> 00:07:37.710
on a Shop Vac, or shitting in a Sop Vac. Really,
either. OK, how much air flow, though? You

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:41.300
need to know, because if you have got too
much air flow you, all suction, you could

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:49.020
have some serious, uncomfortable-ness. Basically,
you got to test it, so you have to hold the

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:53.779
entire toilet over to Ellington Field and
get it on one of those planes, that does the,

00:07:53.779 --> 00:08:01.909
C9, like this, and as the plane goes over
and down into a dive you have about 22 seconds

00:08:01.909 --> 00:08:05.129
of zero gravity. OK, now, think about that.

00:08:05.129 --> 00:08:06.129
[Laughter]

00:08:06.129 --> 00:08:13.219
You are testing your toilet. This means, some
poor schmo from the Waste Management Systems

00:08:13.219 --> 00:08:20.249
Department has 22 seconds in which to perform.
And I was never on, sadly, on one of these

00:08:20.249 --> 00:08:24.849
flights, but I did talked to someone who had
been on boarded, it was Charles Borland, and

00:08:24.849 --> 00:08:30.029
he is the guy who designed a lot of the food
systems that they use during Apollo and even

00:08:30.029 --> 00:08:34.959
through Shuttle. And Charles Borland was there,
he had like 22 different food system packaging,

00:08:34.959 --> 00:08:39.779
various things he was testing to make sure
it would work, and he said: "You know, they

00:08:39.779 --> 00:08:44.980
had the toilet people, they had a curtain
that they pulled, but you could see, you know,

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:48.990
underneath the curtains and as we got into
the dive you'd see everything start to hover

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:54.069
and you'd hear like, 'Go, go, go, go, go!'"

00:08:54.069 --> 00:08:55.069
[Laughter]

00:08:55.069 --> 00:08:58.190
And the guy failed. I mean—

00:08:58.190 --> 00:08:59.300
[Laughter]

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:05.380
I mean, who wouldn't? If it were me, I mean,
my colon would be like, you know, sorry boss,

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:13.170
10am absolute latest I can do for you. So,
this is why at NASA Ames, there is an engineer

00:09:13.170 --> 00:09:20.339
and part of his job was to design a very high
fidelity fecal simulant. So now, no poor guy

00:09:20.339 --> 00:09:25.629
from Waste Management Systems has to go ride
the Vomit Comet, on the toilet, and try to

00:09:25.629 --> 00:09:32.610
go in 22 seconds. So this is a very long-winded,
rambling way of saying that everything gets

00:09:32.610 --> 00:09:41.839
simulated in the most entertaining ways. Let's
see, they also do--the psychological elements

00:09:41.839 --> 00:09:47.000
of long duration space flight are a little
easier and cheaper to simulate. Basically

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.500
you put people in a box for a while and you
watch them and you see, give them difficult

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:56.740
stressful situations and you put in people
of different gender and culture and you see

00:09:56.740 --> 00:10:02.430
how they don't get along and fist fights break
out and people claim sexual harassment so,

00:10:02.430 --> 00:10:08.350
there are all kinds of these interesting psychological
simulations. It's a little difficult, as I

00:10:08.350 --> 00:10:14.260
as a reporter, I like to go on scene and be
there, so I thought, well I'll apply. There

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:19.060
was one called Mars500, you might have heard
of, that is underway right now. And there

00:10:19.060 --> 00:10:23.130
was a little three-month trial for Mars500
and there is something going on in Moscow.

00:10:23.130 --> 00:10:29.060
A bunch of boxes underground floor of the
Institute for Biomedical Problems, which if

00:10:29.060 --> 00:10:31.750
it were here it would be Institute of Biomedical
Solutions.

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:33.340
[Laughter]

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:40.529
But in Moscow, it's Problems. So, the Russian
Space Agency and the European Space Agency

00:10:40.529 --> 00:10:46.350
we're gonna do this stimulation, Simulated
Mars Mission, and to work out the kinks, they

00:10:46.350 --> 00:10:50.279
thought, OK, we'll do a three-month lead-up
just to see how everything goes and I thought,

00:10:50.279 --> 00:10:55.529
well, that would be very interesting for the
book, so I applied and I got, as far as I

00:10:55.529 --> 00:11:00.399
got. I passed the medical portion of it and
various sort of filling out the form, or whatever,

00:11:00.399 --> 00:11:04.460
and they said, OK, you made it onto the next
stage, and I said, OK, great. They said, we'll

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:10.829
be calling you. So, some weeks went by and
the phone rings and it's 4 in the morning

00:11:10.829 --> 00:11:16.810
and I don't really take care to hide my irritation,
that it's 4 in the morning and I picked it

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:20.879
up and "Hello," and "This is the European
Space Agency and we understand you've applied."

00:11:20.879 --> 00:11:26.389
and "Don't you know what coast? I don't live
in Europe," you know, I was just the bitch

00:11:26.389 --> 00:11:31.121
that I am, especially at 4 in the morning.
Well, that was part of the test. So I did

00:11:31.121 --> 00:11:32.121
not get chosen--

00:11:32.121 --> 00:11:33.121
[Laughter]

00:11:33.121 --> 00:11:42.149
--to be part of the Mars500 lead-up. But anyway,
it's an interesting situation, the psychological--I

00:11:42.149 --> 00:11:48.310
got called a bunch, when the Chilean miners
were underground. This is sort of an analogist

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:52.800
situation, they call it "isolation and confinement,"
and it does a very unique number on the human

00:11:52.800 --> 00:12:00.600
psyche. You a, space is a really, it's a frustrating
place, because you're stuck in this room and

00:12:00.600 --> 00:12:05.190
you can't, you really soaking in it. If something
is bothering you, you can't just run out,

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:09.019
slam the door and go for a drive. All the
things that you may do to relive stress, like

00:12:09.019 --> 00:12:17.879
going for a jog, or having a drink, or a hot
bath, or shopping, whatever it is that you

00:12:17.879 --> 00:12:22.070
do to relive stress you can't do that in space,
so you get this frustration that builds up

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:29.700
and up, and in a long mission it starts to
kind of metastasize to just anger and hostility

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:34.810
and psychologists will tell you, anger wants
an outlet, so if somebody is gonna get it.

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:40.040
You are gonna reach the breaking point and
get mad at someone. And in space you don't

00:12:40.040 --> 00:12:45.129
want to get mad at your fellows crew members
because you depend on them for your survival,

00:12:45.129 --> 00:12:49.769
you are only gonna make them mad or worse.
So what happens, and it's called "Displacement,"

00:12:49.769 --> 00:12:54.199
and what happens, and you see it in the mission
transcripts, the astronauts would get really

00:12:54.199 --> 00:12:58.439
irritable with Mission Control. And those
poor guys at Mission Control—people are

00:12:58.439 --> 00:13:03.029
just like: "I can't do that because it's on
the other side of the capsule. You don't even

00:13:03.029 --> 00:13:09.210
not where it is." It's really, you see, in
Gemini 7 there is this moment Captain Lovell,

00:13:09.210 --> 00:13:16.110
again, for him it wasn't Mission Control,
it was the nutritionist, Dr. Chance. You're

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:20.870
reading along on the transcript and you'll
see lot of going; "A memo to Dr. Chance: chicken

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:27.319
a la king, serial number 645, cannot even
get material through neck of packaging!" And

00:13:27.319 --> 00:13:32.860
then like a minute later, "Further memo to
Dr. Chance: Chicken a la king all over the

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:33.860
window at this time.--

00:13:33.860 --> 00:13:35.610
[Laughter]

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:42.649
--At $300 a meal, I think you guys can do
better!" Just really. Just letting them have

00:13:42.649 --> 00:13:48.720
it. Hopefully Dr. Chance was getting some
counseling, like don]t take it personally,

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:56.939
he's just feeling frustrated. So, yes, poor
Dr. Chance. Anyway, so, simulations. What

00:13:56.939 --> 00:14:01.490
else was I going to tell you guys about?

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:13.490
I can do this with one hand [unscrewing bottle
cap]. The third thing you can do with your

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:19.529
anger. You don't take it out on Dr. Chance
or Mission Control people, you turn it inward,

00:14:19.529 --> 00:14:23.709
then you get depression. That's the classic
way to create depression in an individual

00:14:23.709 --> 00:14:31.820
is to have no real outlet for anger and frustration
and turn it inward, and this, you would see

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:36.880
in some of the Mir missions and longer IS
(International Space) Station missions. There

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:41.160
was some serious depression going on at some
of the astronauts and cosmonauts have been

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:45.829
more candid about in recent years. I've interviewed
a couple of cosmonauts who had spent six month

00:14:45.829 --> 00:14:52.649
together on Mir. Yuri Romanenko and Aleksandr
Laveykin and I asked Laveykin about this.

00:14:52.649 --> 00:14:56.990
I said. "Did you find it a very depressing
experience?" and he said, "Mary, there were

00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:01.199
times when I wanted to hang myself but it's
weightlessness--"

00:15:01.199 --> 00:15:02.209
[Laughter]

00:15:02.209 --> 00:15:10.550
--but you can't." The cosmonauts are really.
Sometimes it was a little difficult to get

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:16.800
the kind of access I wanted or the kind of
candor that I wanted at NASA so I went all

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:23.170
the way to Star City, outside Moscow. And
these guys were great, I was gonna say, they

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:30.050
are so down to earth. That's not the best
term for an astronaut, cosmonaut, but we just

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:34.119
had really interesting conversations. You
could ask all the things that NASA, NASA they

00:15:34.119 --> 00:15:37.620
were trying to be helpful in their way but
they just don't really like when people bring

00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:47.879
up things like sex. But in Moscow, I remember
I said, you know, "You guys, six month, a

00:15:47.879 --> 00:15:52.920
couple of guys in a can. You're young, healthy
men, was that kind of awkward? What do you

00:15:52.920 --> 00:15:58.259
do with your sexual urges?" He said, "Mary,
everybody asks me this," and I said, "Sasha,"

00:15:58.259 --> 00:16:02.639
that was his nickname, "Sasha, how are you
making sex in space?" and he says, "Of course,

00:16:02.639 --> 00:16:09.170
by hand." [Laughter] And he said, "Why is
this an issue? Who cares?" So, anyway he was

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:16.860
a lovely and delightful person. I think I'll
read one little passage because it's kind

00:16:16.860 --> 00:16:19.639
of fun and then maybe I'll open it up for
questions, because I don't know how much time

00:16:19.639 --> 00:16:20.639
we have?

00:16:20.639 --> 00:16:23.579
&gt;&gt;Unknown speaker: Plenty of time.

00:16:23.579 --> 00:16:31.990
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: OK. I'm going to read a short
section from the book, because it's kind of

00:16:31.990 --> 00:16:32.990
a fun section.

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:42.730
So, this is Apollo 16 and we have Charlie
Duke and John Young who have been tooling

00:16:42.730 --> 00:16:48.490
around on the moon, surface of the moon, collecting
rocks, doing their thing up there. And now

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:55.019
they are in a radio debriefing with Mission
Control. "Out of the blue," Young declares,

00:16:55.019 --> 00:16:58.809
"I got the farts again. I got them again,
Charlie. I don't know what the hell gives

00:16:58.809 --> 00:17:03.550
it to me. I think is acid in the stomach.
Following Apollo 15, in which low potassium

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:08.669
levels were blamed for heart arrhythmias of
the crew, NASA had put potassium-laced, orange,

00:17:08.669 --> 00:17:13.029
grapefruit and other citrus drinks on the
menu.

00:17:13.029 --> 00:17:17.089
"Tang. Young kept going, it's all there on
the mission transcript. I mean, I haven't

00:17:17.089 --> 00:17:21.260
eatten this much citrus fruit in 20 years
and I'll tell you one thing, in another 12

00:17:21.260 --> 00:17:25.289
fucking days I'm never eating anymore and
if they offer to serve me potassium with my

00:17:25.289 --> 00:17:31.340
breakfast, I'm gonna throw up. I like an occasional
orange. I really do, but I'll be damned if

00:17:31.340 --> 00:17:37.070
I'm gonna be buried in oranges." Moments later,
Mission Control comes on the line and provides

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:42.710
Young with yet more fodder for indigestion:
'Uh, Ryan, this is Houston.' 'Yes, sir.' 'OK.

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:43.980
You have a hot mike.'

