00:35:56.080 --> 00:35:57.080
that we would not like?

00:35:57.080 --> 00:35:58.080
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: Oh. Yes. There are millions
of one. I mean, NASA, the whole Space Program

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:01.940
is just delightfully surreal and ludicrous.
I mean, look what we're doing. We're putting

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:06.720
human beings up at this place where nothing
for them, where they don't belong. The engineering

00:36:06.720 --> 00:36:13.490
challenges, the psychological challenges.
Plus it's a government organization. I would

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:20.620
love for somebody as an insider to write a
wonderful book about NASA. Mike Mullane, the

00:36:20.620 --> 00:36:25.590
astronaut Mike Mullane did a book that was
pretty close to that. He really did. He was

00:36:25.590 --> 00:36:32.050
very forthcoming about the whole culture at
NASA and what it's like. I recommend that

00:36:32.050 --> 00:36:36.920
book as a sort of inside point of view. I
was an outsider, so I was struggling to get

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:44.120
whatever little scraps I can. But I had this
sense that, yes, untold fabulous stories out

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:46.120
there, waiting to be put into a book by somebody
who works there now. OK, one more question.

00:36:46.120 --> 00:36:47.120
Yes.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:51.580
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #9: Can you talk about
how people deal with boredom in space?

00:36:51.580 --> 00:37:02.880
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: The boredom in space? Yeah.
It's tough because there is not a lot recreational

00:37:02.880 --> 00:37:09.470
opportunities. People bring musical instruments.
One of the Japanese astronauts brought a karaoke

00:37:09.470 --> 00:37:14.280
machine, which I think could possibly have
created some interesting psychological tension.

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:16.840
[Laughter]

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:25.010
I'm sure that e-readers--The Kindle had not
been passed for outgassing testing yet. Everything

00:37:25.010 --> 00:37:30.350
that flies out there get sent to this guy,
he's like NASA's nose, and he sniffs it and

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:36.441
do these tests for volatiles, to make sure
there is nothing harmful coming off. And the

00:37:36.441 --> 00:37:41.400
Kindle had not yet been ytested, or any of
the other e-readers. There is reading, obviously,

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:47.630
but there is some time, particularly in the
long duration missions, there is not eight

00:37:47.630 --> 00:37:53.460
hours a day of work to be done and the boredom
was apparently, was part of the reasons some

00:37:53.460 --> 00:37:58.050
of the astronauts were very depressed. That
was the main contributing factor, was that

00:37:58.050 --> 00:38:02.730
there was nothing to do and the scenery never
changes. What?

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:06.120
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #4: [inaudible]

00:38:06.120 --> 00:38:13.200
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: Yes. Anything that's portable.
They have a weight cut-off for how much personal

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:20.770
stuff you can bring, but you can bring up
games, guitars. People have brought up, so.

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:24.080
Certainly not a Ping-Pong table, for various
reasons, but--

00:38:24.080 --> 00:38:25.080
[Laughter]

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:34.620
--maybe you'll figure out something up to
do with it different. Whatever you can bring,

00:38:34.620 --> 00:38:38.980
Sudoku, like portable stuff. Kind of like
a camping trip or a backpacking trip, where

00:38:38.980 --> 00:38:46.710
my husband and I always bring Travel Scrabble.
You bring something that's not going to put

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:51.360
you over the limit on your weight requirement.
Yes.

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:54.190
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #10: Were there jugglers
or any kind of circus performers [inaudible]?

00:38:54.190 --> 00:38:57.120
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: Were there jugglers or circus
performers? Someone brought a boomerang up

00:38:57.120 --> 00:39:03.790
on either the shuttle or the ISS. I thought,
who allowed that? Like hurling things around

00:39:03.790 --> 00:39:10.610
in a delicate machine. But interestingly enough
the boomerang flew OK. That doesn't make sense

00:39:10.610 --> 00:39:18.890
to me. I don't know why, I don't just think
it will work. A juggler, that would be a challenge.

00:39:18.890 --> 00:39:20.050
One more question. Yes.

00:39:20.050 --> 00:39:22.400
Oh, you were juggling.

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:23.400
[Laughter]

00:39:23.400 --> 00:39:24.400
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #10: [inaudible]

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:25.670
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: I know. Yes.

00:39:25.670 --> 00:39:29.560
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #5: Speaking of the
footnotes, how do you keep focus on those

00:39:29.560 --> 00:39:34.290
wonderful archives? I could imagine ending
up being there for days.

00:39:34.290 --> 00:39:38.100
&gt;&gt;Mary Roach: Yes, How I do keep focus on
those wonderful archives? The trick is not

00:39:38.100 --> 00:39:41.420
keep focus, because when you get distracted
and you go off and you start flipping the

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:46.040
pages of some old back issue on some journal
you find the most amazing things. You may

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:52.070
find your next book in the pages. So I am
a big proponent of following your distractions.

00:39:52.070 --> 00:40:00.460
I am not a terribly productive person in an
archive or elsewhere, but I do allow myself

00:40:00.460 --> 00:40:05.840
the indulgence of going off on tangents. Thanks.
Thank you.

00:40:05.840 --> 00:40:05.950
